                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 181.9202/267: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">General <persName type="from">Bandholtz</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Budapest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-11-30">November 30,
                            1919</date>.<lb/>[Received November 30—2:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>219. Polk from Bandholtz. My officer sent to Roumanian Headquarters quotes
                    General Mardarescu as saying he has no instructions to retire beyond the Tisza
                    and that he should remain there until peace is signed with the Hungarians. That
                    he sees no necessity for liaison with this Mission which was only authorized to
                    arrange for evacuation to the Tisza and that all questions affecting territory
                    now occupied should be taken up with his Government. This is the very attitude
                    anticipated in my previous reports to Ammission and strengthens the opinion
                    expressed in my other message this date<note n="78" xml:id="d360fn78">Not found
                        in Department files.</note> as regards Mission. Reported that Maniu who is a
                    satellite of Bratiano has been appointed Roumanian Prime Minister.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bandholtz</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
